    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but it sounds a bit scary. Is there any way for these things to be \"hidden\" in the fine print? Like, are there specific types of breaches or wording they use to make the liability even bigger than it looks at first glance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely, and that's where the real danger lurks, which is often hidden in the fine print like a particularly sneaky little poison dart in a pile of useful-looking moss. You're right to be wary; these contracts are often written by lawyers who enjoy making things as broad as possible, much like a massive, sprawling patch of swamp where you never know which patch of mud will swallow your boots.\n\nThe biggest danger areas are usually in the scope of what constitutes a \"breach\" or what \"losses\" they are covering. Look out for language that uses sweeping terms like \"any and all,\" \"including but not limited to,\" or phrases that tie your liability to *their* actions as well. Sometimes, they might try to make your indemnity cover things that are technically outside your control—like if their own information was flawed, but they still try to pin the resulting lawsuit on you.\n\nIf you see language that makes your obligation limitless, that's a huge red flag, as it suggests you could be liable for catastrophic losses, not just small mistakes. It's almost always better to try and limit the scope—for example, limiting your liability only to direct damages caused by your negligence, not every",
      "source": "target",
